 Margaret adjusted the pillow behind Henry's head, plumping it just the way he liked—firm enough to support, soft enough to dream. The afternoon light filtered through the window, casting a golden glow across the room where Henry sat in his wheelchair, staring at the sky.

 "Look," Henry said suddenly, pointing a trembling finger toward the window. "That cloud looks like a swan. Just like the ones at the lake where I proposed."

 Margaret's heart caught. Most days, the dementia kept Henry trapped in a fog, but moments like this—when he remembered—felt like gifts dropped from heaven.

 "You were exaggerating when you said you'd jump in if I said no," Margaret said softly, sitting beside him and taking his hand.

 Henry turned to her, his eyes clearing for a precious moment. "And you were exaggerating when you said you'd love me forever. But here we are."

 Margaret felt tears prick her eyes. For months, she had complained to her sister about the exhaustion, the grief of watching him fade, the unfairness of it all. But looking at him now—this man who had built a life with her, who still found swans in the clouds—she realized she hadn't been exaggerating at all. The love was the only real thing in the room.

 "I did promise forever," she whispered.

 Henry squeezed her hand. "And forever is right now."

 Margaret rested her head against his shoulder, understanding at last that love wasn't measured in the ease of a journey, but in the willingness to keep adjusting the pillow, keep pointing out the clouds, keep showing up even when the mind forgets what the heart never does.

